<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="s_complex_numbers_polynomials">
  <title>Complex numbers and polynomials</title>
  <introduction>
    In this section we begin with a brief treatment of the complex numbers <m>\C</m>. One very useful application of the complex numbers is that any polynomial with real coefficients factors as a product of linear terms over <m>\C</m> (<xref ref="cor_fund_alg"/>). Accordingly we will also give a brief review of definitions and properties related to polynomials. All theorems in this section will be given without a proof. The results here are all elementary, with the exception of course of the proof of <xref ref="th_fund_alg" text="custom">the fundamental theorem of algebra</xref>.
  </introduction>
<subsection xml:id="ss_complex_numbers">
  <title>Complex numbers</title>
  <p>
    As we see below, the complex numbers is a number system built by taking the set of all <em>pairs</em> of real numbers and defining operations on these pairs that we call <em>complex addition</em> and <em>complex multiplication</em>.
  </p>
<definition xml:id="d_complex_numbers">
  <idx><h>complex numbers</h></idx>
  <title>Complex numbers</title>
  <notation>
    <usage><m>\C</m></usage>
    <description>complex numbers</description>
  </notation>
  <statement>
  <p>
    The set <m>\C</m> of <term>complex numbers</term>  is defined as the set of all pairs of real numbers: <ie />,
  <me>
    \C=\{(a, b)\colon a, b\in \R\}
  </me>.
</p>
</definition>
<convention>
<p>
  Henceforth we will denote a complex number <m>z=(a,b)</m> as
<men xml:id="eq_complex_notation">
  z=a+bi
</men>.
Furthermore, we will use the notational abbreviations <m>a=a+0i</m>, <m>bi=0+bi</m>, and <m>i=0+1i</m>.
</p>
<p>
  In what follows we will give some arithmetic meaning to the notation <xref ref="eq_complex_notation"/>, but first and foremost it should simply be thought of as an alternative manner of denoting the pair <m>(a,b)</m>.
</p>
</convention>
<definition xml:id="d_complex_arithmetic">
  <idx><h>complex numbers</h><h>addition</h></idx>
  <idx><h>complex numbers</h><h>multiplication</h></idx>

  <title>Complex addition and multiplication</title>

  <statement>
<p>
  We define <term>addition</term> and <term>multiplication</term> operations on <m>\C</m> as follows. Let <m>z=a+bi</m> and <m>w=c+di</m>, where <m>a,b,c,d\in \R</m>.
</p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <title>Complex addition</title>
    <p>
      The <term>sum</term> <m>z+w</m> if defined as 
      <me>
        z+w=(a+c)+(b+d)i</me>.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <title>Complex multiplication</title>
    <p>
      Given <m>z=(a,b)=a+bi</m> and <m>w=(c,d)=c+di</m>, we define
      <me>
        z\, w=(ac-bd)+(ad+bc)i</me>.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</statement>
</definition>
<definition xml:id="d_real_imaginary">
<title>Real and imaginary parts</title>
<statement>
<p>
  Given complex number <m>z=(a,b)=a+bi</m> we define its <term>real part</term> <m>\Re z</m> as <m>\Re z=a</m> and its <term>imaginary part</term> <m>\Im z</m> as <m>\Im z=b</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<remark xml:id="rm_complex_equality">
<title>Complex equality</title>
<statement>
<p>
  Let <m>z=(a,b)=a+bi</m> and <m>w=(c,d)=c+di</m>. According to the definition of equality for tuples (<xref ref="d_cartesian_product" text="global"/>), we have <m>z=w</m> if and only if <m>a=c</m> and <m>b=d</m>: equivalently, if and only if <m>\Re z=\Re w</m> and <m>\Im z=\Im w</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</remark>
<p>
  Our first theorem indicates that complex addition and multiplication satisfy many of the same properies of real addition and multiplication. A number system that satisfies the properties below is called a <em>field</em>.
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_complex_arithmetic_basic">
  <title>Basic properties of complex arithmetic</title>
  <statement>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <title>Commutativity</title>
        <p>
        For all <m>z, w\in \C</m> we have
        <md>
          <mrow>z+ w \amp =  w+z</mrow>
          <mrow> z w  \amp= wz </mrow>
        </md>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
      <title>Associativity</title>
      <p>
      For all <m>z, w, u \in \C</m> we have
      <md>
        <mrow>z+( w+ u) \amp = (z+ w)+ u</mrow>
        <mrow> z( w u)  \amp=(z w) u </mrow>
      </md>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
    <title>Distributivity</title>
    <p>
    For all <m>z, w, u \in \C</m> we have
    <me>
      z( w+ u)=z w+z u
    </me>.
    </p>
  </li>
      <li>
        <title>Additive identity</title>
        <p>
        The complex number <m>0=0+0i\in \C</m> satisfies
        <me>
          0+z=z
        </me>
          for all <m>z\in \C</m>. We call <m>0</m> the <term>additive identity</term> of <m>\C</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Additive inverse</title>
        <p>
        For all <m>z=(a,b)=a+bi\in \C</m> the element <m>-z=(-a,-b)=-a+(-b)i\in \C</m> satisfies
        <me>
          z+ -z=0
        </me>.
        We call <m>-z</m> the <term>additive inverse</term>of <m>z</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Multiplicative identity</title>
        <p>
        The complex number <m>1=1+0i</m> satisfies
        <me>
          1\cdot z=z
        </me>
          for all <m>z\in \C</m>. We call <m>1</m> the <term>multiplicative identity</term> of <m>\C</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Multiplicative inverse</title>
        <p>
        For all <em>nonzero</em> complex numbers <m>z=(a,b)=a+bi\in \C</m> (<ie />, <m>a\ne 0</m> of <m>b\ne 0</m>), the complex number <m>z^{-1}=\frac{a}{a^2+b^2}-\frac{b}{a^2+b^2}i \in \C</m> satisfies
        <me>
          z\,z^{-1}=1
        </me>.
        The complex number <m>z^{-1}</m>, also denoted <m>1/z</m>, is called the <term>multiplicative inverse</term> of <m>z</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</theorem>
    <remark xml:id="rm_complex_reals">
      <title>Complex numbers as extension of the reals</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      From now on we identify the real numbers as a subset of the complex numbers via the injective map
      <md>
        <mrow>\R \amp\rightarrow \C </mrow>
        <mrow> a\amp\mapsto a+0i </mrow>
      </md>.
      It is easy to verify that under this identification the various complex operations agree with their real counterparts when restricting to real numbers: <eg />,
      <md>
        <mrow>(a+0i)+(b+0i) \amp = (a+b)+0i</mrow>
        <mrow> (a+0i)(b+0i)\amp=ab+0i </mrow>
        <mrow> -(a+0i) \amp =-a+0i</mrow>
        <mrow> (a+0i)^{-1} \amp =a^{-1}+0i</mrow>
      </md>.
      This allows us to think of the complex numbers as a larger number system containing the reals, whose arithmetic operations are extensions of real number operations.
    </p>
  </statement>
</remark>
<p>
  We end our introduction to the complex numbers with two further operations: the complex <em>absolute value</em> and <em>complex conjugation</em>. <xref ref="th_complex_conjugation_modulus"/> is an indication of the usefulness of these operations, and articulates how they ineract with the arithmetic complex operations.
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_complex_absolute_conjugation">
  <idx><h>complex numbers</h><h>modulus</h></idx>
  <idx><h>complex numbers</h><h>absolute value</h></idx>
  <idx><h>complex numbers</h><h>conjugation</h></idx>
  <title>Absolute value and complex conjugation</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>z=(a,b)=a+bi</m> be a complex number. The  <term>absolute value</term> (or <term>modulus</term>) of <m>z</m>, denoted <m>\abs{z}</m>, is defined as
      <me>
        \abs{z}=\sqrt{a^2+b^2}
      </me>.
      The <term>complex conjugate</term> of <m>z</m>, denoted <m>\overline{z}</m>, is defined as
      <me>
        \overline{z}=a-bi
      </me>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>
<theorem xml:id="th_complex_conjugation_modulus">
  <title>Properties of conjugation and modulus</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The following properties hold for any complex numbers <m>\boldz</m> and <m>\boldw</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\overline{z+w} \amp =\overline{z}+\overline{w}</mrow>
          <mrow>\overline{zw} \amp =\overline{z}\overline{w}</mrow>
          <mrow> \abs{zw} \amp =\abs{z}\abs{w}</mrow>
        </md>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
            \abs{z}=\sqrt{z\overline{z}}
          </me>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
            z\ne 0\implies z^{-1}=\frac{z}{\abs{z}}
          </me>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <me>
            z\in \R\iff \overline{z}=z
          </me>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</theorem>

</subsection>
</section>
